author: DiamondJackson

description.text:
My design for an in body micro servo based tricopter.
Designed with 3D printing in mind so all is to scale and fairly accurate.
Some of the features include a guided snap fit rotation device that mounts directly to a rounded servo horn. When placing the tail mechanism into the model, it allows the user to slightly asjust for best rotation YAW performance. There is also support on the tail arm. Also, support is added with the elongated body towards the back and a short arm on back. This should reduce vertical play when flying and less torgue on the servo. Some other features included are rotating left and right arms for storage, battery strap slits that also hold the bottom cover plate, extra large bay that can hold 3 12A esc's as well as small vtx.
Totice the pre made hole for the antenna up through the body. This will require an angled connector.
The front end of the frame allows for a 600tvl CCD camera with holes for wiring back to the vtx.
As well, holes are drilled into the bay to allow motor wires to pass through. All wires can exit up to the NAZE32 board. This slot is designed with the NAZE32 board in mind and has the standoff holes. Another function of the design is the back leg rounded support allows for 3mm LED lights. As well, the front of the model has a left and right inset specifically designed for LED strip lights. No holes are for this wiring is provided as it is optional. Holes can be drilled back to the bay.

description.text:
Give your Ticket to Ride games some Disney flavor!  Here's a monorail engine and car, just like you'd find at Disneyland.  
Players start with 45 pieces in a normal game, I'm thinking 20 engines and 25 cars should do it.  That would let you have engine cars at either end of each route.

Print without supports, there are small supports built into the model at the ends of each car.  You can pry them away with a fingernail.  
The stripe on the white train was done by using the Z-pause setting on our Makerbot 2.  I set it for 6mm, changed to red, then stopped it again just as it was finishing it's 59% pass on the cars.

description.text: Replacement game piece for Star Wars trouble game.  If you lost one or more, just print in matching color.

This is a plastic bushing/slider used to hang doors in Arrow sheds (two per door). I noticed ours were worn away to next to nothing, and used the remaining pieces to design a replacement. The sliders can be purchased as part of a "tune up kit" from the manufacturer here (http://www.sheds.com/miva/merchant.mvc?Screen=PROD&Store_Code=S&Product_Code=DK100&Category_Code=A), or you can save $15 and print your own. At its simplest the design is an extruded "H" where the top and bottom slide along folded sheet metal guides. Like the original part, the insides of the pathway narrow down to provide less wiggle. Aside from the guide pins (placed on both sides so that the piece can be used in left and right orientations), there is also a through and through screw hole.

I had a lot of success printing the part with the guide pins on bottom as the STL preview illustrates.  I'm not sure how well the pins would print in any other orientation due to their overhang.
With my TOM and MK6 Stepstruder, the pins printed well as did the screw hole.  The gentle curves on the inside of the guideways caused no real issues on my printer.

title: Game Board - Modular - Tablero
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Originally designed as a game board for Tablero da Gucci. Owing to a lack of tiled game boards that weren't lasercut, I started upon this. To date, the only other printable design I've found is a jig-saw style set by http://www.thingiverse.com/wulfdesign The design purpose was to have a board that allowed flexibility in the colours of the individual squares of the board as well as the pieces that make the gaps separating the squares. By inserting a beam between each adjoining piece this allows control of the spacing between the squares by simply printing a different beam design.
Also, this board is rather large compared to an average chess board. The squares are sized to allow space for shot glasses instead of the smaller game pieces that are commonly seen with most tile board based games. For example, my printed twisted shot glass http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7214. For those interested in the brief version of the details of Tablero da Gucci see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablero_da_Gucci Only built as far as a 5 x 5 board so far due to a plastruder motor failure. Will add some pictures of a board in use once the situation is fixed. Even if you don't specifically need a game board, just flip it over and hang it on the wall. The back side can almost be a piece of art in itself.

The number of parts required will depend upon the number of squares that make up the dimensions of the board. So, for some basic math, using a square or rectangular board that's x by y squares plus a border around the outer edge. corner = 4 (regardless of size)
edge = 2 x + 2 y
edgebeam = 2 ( x + 1 ) + 2 ( y + 1 )
centre = x y
beam = ( x + 1 ) y + ( y + 1 ) * x For example a standard 7x7 Tablero board would be
4 corners
28 edges
32 edgebeams
49 centres
112 beams A Tic-Tac-Toe board would be
4 corners
12 edges
16 edgebeams
9 centres
24 beams A standard 8x8 Chess board would be
4 corners
32 edges
36 edgebeams
64 centres
144 beams And if for some reason you wished for a 3x9 board
4 corners
24 edges
28 edgebeams
27 centres
66 beams Feel free to assemble with a hollow centre or even an L or C shaped board from these pieces. As long as you can figure a way to make use of such a shape. Updated 2012-04-24
Added some photos of the completed board from almost a year ago.
Uploaded the original VariCAD .dwb file as well as the STEP format as that's the only non native format my CAD program will export and load back in as 3d objects.

I started working on a hot end cooler that utilizes an air pump for aquariums. The particular model of pump that I am using has 4 outputs and variable strength. Instead of having one on full blast making the motor the loudest it can go to pump one outlet hard enough to cool the plastic coming out of the hot end and wasting the output of three other valves, I decided to create an adapter to take all four and connect them to one line. You could use it to combine four into one, split one into four, or really what ever you want. The interior channels are all connected so any fluid should flow from one to all and so on. I could have just bought two elbow connecters and three T connectors, for 99 cents each, but I'm a maker, and spending an hour modeling a part and another hour printing the part for a fraction of the cost is what we do. So here you go. In case for some reason you need this kind of stuff, the modeled dimensions are:

Do note that there is a part that you need to 3D print and there are some additional parts that you would require to make yourself this simple DIY battery charger for dNano. Check out http://www.labywiinth.org/ for more details on the Labwiinth project. This is a bracket I manufactured for a Local KC science store to sell with their Labywiinth kits (If you\'re in the KC area, Vince will be doing a workshop July 11th http://hms-beagle.com/Programs.html). The original brackets were designed by Vince and hand cut out of Lexan, but Lexan doesn\'t agree with my laser cutter so these are made of 0.06\" PETG, the same plastic those indestructible blister packs are made out of!

Here\'s what you\'ll need to make this project:
  • A labyrinth game (you can find them in thrift stores and online in various places)
  • 2 servo brackets
  • 2 standard size hobby servos
  • 4x #6 1/4\" Wood screws per servo mount
  • About 1-1/4\" of 1\" heat shrink tubing per servo mount
  • Any hardware/software you choose to control the 2 servos
    • Step 0 - Making a Bracket
    Here\'s my settings for cutting on my 35W Epilog if you\'ve got access to a laser (and some .06\" PETG):
    18% Speed
    40% Power
    500Hz
    I believe I used the standard acrylic settings for the raster part (the channels on the bracket you fold) and left the masking material on. Different settings may work better for you, these just limited the yellowing of PETG and cut it nicely in my setup. Ponoko used to offer PETG, but unfortunately they seem to have pulled it for some reason. Since the brackets are pretty simple you can always just use the design as a template and cut them out by hand. If you still want a laser cut bracket and don\'t have access to a cutter, shoot me an email and I\'d be happy to send some spares to you. Step 1 - Bend the Bracket
    I\'ve attached a PDF included with the kits that explains how to bend the brackets after cutting. Step 2 - Attach the Servo
    To attach the servo to the knob of the labyrinth game, I left the standard horn included with the servo on and slipped 1\" heat shrink tubing over it and the knob then shrank the tubing until it was coupled well. Try to get the servo centered on the knob, if it\'s not the servo will be off balance and torque the bracket. You don\'t have to worry if it\'s not perfect though, the brackets are relatively flexible. Step 3 - Attach the Bracket
    To attach the brackets to the labyrinth game, I used 1/4\" #6 wood screws. I didn\'t screw down the servo because it seemed pretty secure as it was, but the mounting holes are there should you choose to. Step 4 - Control It
    You can now hook up just about any microcontroller or servo controller to the game now and control it any way you want. I hooked up a 2-channel RC car receiver to mine to do a test run and it worked out well. You can also hook up an Arduino and control it with a Wii Balance board (I\'ll post software soon) or try to get a computer to play the game for you (which was one of the original goals of the project). Links:
    A quick Google search turned up the same board that I\'m currently using:
    http://www.epartyunlimited.com/labyrinth-wooden-board-game.html
    You should be able to find one cheaper if you look around. Vince\'s site:
    http://someoneknows.wordpress.com
    There\'s a project in the works to make a HUGE Labywiinth for the local science museum that uses the same Wii Balance board control and another smaller version to take on tour. You can follow the progress on Vince\'s blog. UPDATE:
    Jestin (the guy that started this whole thing and coded up the Labywiinth control software) posted up the code for this here:
    https://sourceforge.net/projects/labywiinth/
    You'll need wiipluspluslib to get it working as well (and a Linux box with a Bluetooth addapter):
    http://sourceforge.net/projects/libwiiplusplus/

description.text: Stamp your things with a recycling code! Inspired by a comment on this article suggesting we have a subroutine that printed a recycling mark on every part we make: http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2011/04/polite-houseguests-print-and-repair.html

Using Inkscape:
  • Set font to Bitstream Vera Sans, font size 144
  • Add text, press CTRL-U to enter unicode code number for the type of plastic, ABS is type 7 so it's code is 2679, press enter. See codes at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resin_identification_code
  • Select symbol, right click, object properties give it a name like recycle, click set
  • File -> Save As -> EPS, check convert texts to paths, limit export to object with id set in previous step
  • Run: pstoedit -dt -f dxf:-polyaslines recycle_7.eps recycle_7.dxf
  • Plug it into recycle_maker.scad, might need to play with the origin and scale to get it into a nice size, compile it to an stl and use something like Pleasant3D or ReplicatorG to center it
  • Now you can stamp it into your model like I did in recycleinate.scad!
    • PS: I had to simplify and remesh the dalek model in meshlab in order to get openscad to process it correctly. I put the recycle logo on the bottom, so download it or view it in thingiview in order to see it. PPS: not all recylcing centers will recycle type 7 plastics, check with them to make sure they take ABS. Type 7 is a catch all code and includes PLA, but PLA isn't recyclable, it's compostable (in comercial composting facilities that is).

Simple add on x-tensioner. The I3 does not have a way to adjust the tension on the x belt. Other tensioners require replacing parts but this one simply slides into place in just a few minutes.

I noticed that the x axis rods were fixed on the motor end but slid through the plastic on the other end. The frame keeps the tension on the x axis belt. If you push on the smooth rods they slide through the mount and tension the belt so that's what this mod does. The openscad files can be modified (set new values the the variables at the top of the file) if needed. The U shaped part needs an M3 30mm bolt put through it so that it looks like a tuning fork. It is then inserted into the mount until the clips come through and click into place (see photo).
The outside bar is then placed over the M3 and the ends of the rods. Add a nut and tighten to remove any slack in the belt. Enjoy!

title: Button Wrench Tool to work on IGT slot machine buttons, or similar

description.text:
Needed this in a pinch and it was easy enough to make up, so here it is!
Tool is used to remove the nut that holds the buttons in slot machines and maybe other types of gaming equipment.
I made one shallow and one deep socket version depending on the switch setup. Very easy to make. Enjoy!

Simple to print. You can print in it's current orientation without support, or flip it for more stability on the bed, but I would use support then for the internal dimension change.
The size fits very snug on the nut. I ended up resizing it by 1.005 and that was perfect for me.
I used PLA in my case, with .3mm layers and 3 perimeters. I used 70% infill, but I think it basically did 100% anyway.

description.text: This is a great little spool holder and line guide that I designed from viewing and trying other designs that just didn't quite work for me. The tolerances for the threaded rod are off set by .2mm for shrink factors. The threaded rod is 6.1 mm in diameter that you can find at your local hardware store which I just had laying around, you will need 4 of them each being about 80mm in length and 16 nuts (longer if using a wider spool which mine is 54.5mm wide). The bearings this took me awhile to figure out; I got all 4 of them from Fastenal product ID "608 ZZ" and there characteristics are 8mm ID x 22mm. I had a couple of issues with the line quide hole not popping right outs but an exacto knife fixed that. I hope you like the design :-)

This is a non-printed print bed expansion. This uses the stock print bed end frames with new rods and angle aluminum, to hold a steel plate that will give you roughly a 15 1/2" x 6" print surface, if you upgrade your Y-axis also.

Vitamins:
(1) 36" tool steel drill rod from McMaster Carr, Part # 88625K67
(1) 6" x 18" 16-gauge plain steel sheet metal plate from Home Depot, SKU # 475130
(2) 3/4" x 1/2" x 36" Aluminum Flat Angle, 1/16" thick from Home Depot, SKU # 550764
(2) M3-10mm socket head cap screws
(4) M3-16mm socket head cap screws
(2) M3 nuts
(1) 24" length of GT2 belt (I got mine from Amazon)
(1) roll of double sided tape The drill rod will need to be cut in half. They typically come slightly over-length, so mine wound up coming out to 18 1/8" long. Bevel/smooth the ends, and use them in place of the standard X-axis rods, attaching them to the stock ends with zip ties in the same way the original rods were attached. The cut list for the angle aluminum pieces will need to be customized to fit your individual rod length. The measurements in the PDF's above show how the parts lay out.
Cut the front and back long pieces to 476mm. These will support the front and rear of the plate.
Cut two pieces approximately 142mm long. These will go on the stock wood end brackets. You will need to notch them to clear the X-axis rods.
The front and rear pieces go on top of these. The rear should be flush and square with the back edge of the wooden end brackets. This is visible in the second picture above.
Cut two pieces approximately 114mm long. These will go on top of the 142mm end pieces you cut above. The purpose of them is to level the ends and fill in the gap between the front and rear pieces. These pieces will also need to be notched to clear the X-axis rods. 3mm holes are drilled to match up with the holes in the wooden end pieces. On mine, they measured 5.5mm and 108mm from the back edge. You will want to verify on yours before you drill. The rear-most and middle hole are 8mm in from the ends, and the front-most hole is 6mm from the end. This hole is 140mm from the rear, and is mainly to attach the front piece to the lower end pieces. M3-16mm screws are used to attach the end pieces to the wooden ends, and M3-10mm screws with M3 nuts are used to attach the front piece to the lower end pieces. Once everything is square and snug, put double-sided tape around the outside edge of the plate. Square up the plate with the frame and install it. You may need to notch one end slightly to clear the screw heads.
